00:10:09,050 --> 00:10:12,350
And so by default, IAM
users don't have access

247
00:10:12,350 --> 00:10:14,900
to really anything.

248
00:10:14,900 --> 00:10:18,530
The best practice here, and I've
even said it a few times now,

249
00:10:18,530 --> 00:10:21,180
is to follow this principle
of least privilege.

250
00:10:21,180 --> 00:10:23,540
So basically, to
access something,

251
00:10:23,540 --> 00:10:26,360
you need to be granted
the access to it.

252
00:10:26,360 --> 00:10:28,920
By default, you have
access to nothing.

253
00:10:28,920 --> 00:10:30,590
The reason we do this,
it's a little bit

254
00:10:30,590 --> 00:10:32,780
annoying from
management standpoint

255
00:10:32,780 --> 00:10:37,050
because then you're obligated
to constantly grant access,

256
00:10:37,050 --> 00:10:38,640
grant access, grant access.

257
00:10:38,640 --> 00:10:40,502
But from a security
perspective, it's

258
00:10:40,502 --> 00:10:41,960
way, way better
because there's not

259
00:10:41,960 --> 00:10:45,140
some sort of account that's
just looming out there

260
00:10:45,140 --> 00:10:47,840
that shouldn't be
accessing something.

261
00:10:47,840 --> 00:10:52,730
It could even be something where
maybe you work for a company,

262
00:10:52,730 --> 00:10:54,960
and after somebody
gets fired or let go,

263
00:10:54,960 --> 00:10:58,650
they should lose access
to their account.

264
00:10:58,650 --> 00:11:01,700
But for whatever reason, it
doesn't instantly knock it down.

265
00:11:01,700 --> 00:11:03,920
Well, we want to make
sure that they only

266
00:11:03,920 --> 00:11:06,350
have the least
privilege, the least

267
00:11:06,350 --> 00:11:08,392
access necessary
for their tasks such

268
00:11:08,392 --> 00:11:10,600
that they can't all of a
sudden do some other damage.

269
00:11:10,600 --> 00:11:12,840
We can at least
monitor or we know

270
00:11:12,840 --> 00:11:16,090
that they'd be constrained to
some region of AWS resources.

271
00:11:16,090 --> 00:11:19,720
And so that's this idea of
principles of least privilege.

272
00:11:19,720 --> 00:11:23,850
So you can see here the
IAM user group or role will

273
00:11:23,850 --> 00:11:26,470
be granted full access
to EC2 instances,

274
00:11:26,470 --> 00:11:30,310
but then could be granted read
only access to the S3 bucket.

275
00:11:30,310 --> 00:11:32,050
If it needed write
access, we would then

276
00:11:32,050 --> 00:11:34,718
have to explicitly
grant it, write access.

277
00:11:34,718 --> 00:11:36,510
And so the idea again
being that everything

278
00:11:36,510 --> 00:11:38,220
is very, very explicit.

279
00:11:38,220 --> 00:11:41,670
If it's not explicitly
stated, it doesn't happen.

280
00:11:41,670 --> 00:11:44,760
We do this via the IAM
policies we talked about,

281
00:11:44,760 --> 00:11:47,410
and the IAM policy, as we
said, is just a document.

282
00:11:47,410 --> 00:11:50,940
It's a JSON, JavaScript Object
Notation, we'll see this a lot,

283
00:11:50,940 --> 00:11:53,400
whether in this course or just
kind of throughout your time

284
00:11:53,400 --> 00:11:56,820
in working in the tech
world, JSON documents

285
00:11:56,820 --> 00:11:57,720
are fairly common.

286
00:11:57,720 --> 00:11:59,220
And it's just
something that's going

287
00:11:59,220 --> 00:12:03,030
to list the permissions in a
nice almost dictionary format

288
00:12:03,030 --> 00:12:05,370
of the permissions that
allow or deny access

289
00:12:05,370 --> 00:12:07,006
to the very specific resources.

290
00:12:09,890 --> 00:12:12,090
There's two types of policies.

291
00:12:12,090 --> 00:12:15,450
And again, I apologize that
it's a lot of just things.

292
00:12:15,450 --> 00:12:17,458
The idea is not for
you to memorize this.

293
00:12:17,458 --> 00:12:20,000
So if you don't feel like you
are picking it all up right now

294
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:22,710
or you don't remember these
things, that's perfectly OK.

295
00:12:22,710 --> 00:12:25,090
My goal is to introduce
them, and so that you

296
00:12:25,090 --> 00:12:26,340
know have these as a resource.

297
00:12:26,340 --> 00:12:27,610
You can come back
to this video, you

298
00:12:27,610 --> 00:12:29,443
can come back to these
slides and figure out

299
00:12:29,443 --> 00:12:32,640
the exact specific thing you
need for your task at hand.

300
00:12:32,640 --> 00:12:34,470
But it's not to
memorize everything.

301
00:12:34,470 --> 00:12:35,887
So don't stress on that.

302
00:12:35,887 --> 00:12:37,470
We're never going
to test you and say,

303
00:12:37,470 --> 00:12:39,110
what are the
characteristics of identity

304
00:12:39,110 --> 00:12:41,030
based policy What's the
characteristic of resource based

305
00:12:41,030 --> 00:12:41,840
policy?

306
00:12:41,840 --> 00:12:45,478
But if you do take the AWS
Cloud Practitioner exam,

307
00:12:45,478 --> 00:12:48,020
you will be expected to know
these things and the differences

308
00:12:48,020 --> 00:12:51,000
between resource based policy
and identity based policy.

309
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:53,270
And so that's why we want
to give you these resources

310
00:12:53,270 --> 00:12:57,330
so you can study them if that's
something you'd like to do.

311
00:12:57,330 --> 00:13:00,790
But getting back to it, we
have two types of policies.

312
00:13:00,790 --> 00:13:03,990
And remember, these are those
JSON documents that explicitly

313
00:13:03,990 --> 00:13:06,280
allow or deny access.

314
00:13:06,280 --> 00:13:11,140
The identity based policy is
attached to an IAM entity.

315
00:13:11,140 --> 00:13:14,910
It will be attached to a user,
a group or a role, right.

316
00:13:14,910 --> 00:13:18,420
These policies will specify
what can be performed

317
00:13:18,420 --> 00:13:20,880
and what can't be performed.

318
00:13:20,880 --> 00:13:23,045
Remember that the least
privileged process

319
00:13:23,045 --> 00:13:24,670
or the principle
of least privilege

320
00:13:24,670 --> 00:13:27,000
states that you won't
have access to anything

321
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:28,950
unless explicitly granted.

322
00:13:28,950 --> 00:13:33,870
But you can also explicitly
deny as well too so that there's

323
00:13:33,870 --> 00:13:36,930
no worry or there's no chance
that they could maybe get access

324
00:13:36,930 --> 00:13:38,180
through some other means.

325
00:13:38,180 --> 00:13:39,610
It's going to
explicitly deny it.

326
00:13:39,610 --> 00:13:41,650
So that is an option
as well, though again,

327
00:13:41,650 --> 00:13:46,350
it's almost a redundant
step in most cases.

328
00:13:46,350 --> 00:13:49,020
You can attach a single
policy to multiple entities

329
00:13:49,020 --> 00:13:51,410
as well too, and that's
often very common.

330
00:13:51,410 --> 00:13:57,360
So it might be that I assign
or I create an IAM policy that

331
00:13:57,360 --> 00:14:03,430
is for data 3600 level access,
and I assign that to a role.

332
00:14:03,430 --> 00:14:05,760
Well, that role may get
assigned to some individuals

333
00:14:05,760 --> 00:14:07,530
or maybe I'll have
a TA that needs

334
00:14:07,530 --> 00:14:09,360
to play around with
some things and see

335
00:14:09,360 --> 00:14:10,930
how it works from
their perspective,

336
00:14:10,930 --> 00:14:13,860
and so I assign them that role
temporarily so they can play

337
00:14:13,860 --> 00:14:16,475
around with it, see what it's
like, from your environment,

338
00:14:16,475 --> 00:14:18,600
and then they can be assigned
a different role that

339
00:14:18,600 --> 00:14:21,190
would change their access
to level access or something

340
00:14:21,190 --> 00:14:22,010
like that.

341
00:14:22,010 --> 00:14:25,540
And then I can also take that
IAM policy, that identity based

342
00:14:25,540 --> 00:14:28,610
policy, and assign it to
the user group as well too.

343
00:14:28,610 --> 00:14:30,850
That is going to be you
guys here at the data 3600

344
00:14:30,850 --> 00:14:32,570
class or the IS 3600 class.

345
00:14:32,570 --> 00:14:36,070
Sorry, I get the
prefixes mixed up.

346
00:14:36,070 --> 00:14:39,650
And also, a single entity
can have multiple policies.

347
00:14:39,650 --> 00:14:46,490
So you could be assigned the
data 30 or the IS 3600 policy,

348
00:14:46,490 --> 00:14:49,270
but you could also
be assigned-- maybe

349
00:14:49,270 --> 00:14:52,330
you're working on an ASC
project for the Department.

350
00:14:52,330 --> 00:14:54,460
And so you could also
be assigned-- well,

351
00:14:54,460 --> 00:14:56,650
I'm going to give you a
little bit of extra access

352
00:14:56,650 --> 00:15:01,960
that is for a project we're
working on that needs access

353
00:15:01,960 --> 00:15:03,560
to specific S3 buckets.

354
00:15:03,560 --> 00:15:08,660
So you'll get the policy
for project 10 ASC project.

355
00:15:08,660 --> 00:15:11,140
And the idea here
is that, again,

356
00:15:11,140 --> 00:15:13,060
the reason we want
to allow that--

357
00:15:13,060 --> 00:15:17,110
and also this is why we have
explicit deny statements too

358
00:15:17,110 --> 00:15:21,590
in policies, is that maybe
in the IS 3600 class,

359
00:15:21,590 --> 00:15:25,490
I give you a blanket, you don't
have access to S3 right now.

360
00:15:25,490 --> 00:15:28,630
Maybe it's early on, so I
don't want you accessing S3.

361
00:15:28,630 --> 00:15:30,590
Well, then it might be
that for this project,

362
00:15:30,590 --> 00:15:33,970
you need access to a
specific S3 bucket.

363
00:15:33,970 --> 00:15:37,990
If I have an explicit blanket
deny on all S3 buckets,

364
00:15:37,990 --> 00:15:41,580
that will supersede access to
anything-- any other specific S3

365
00:15:41,580 --> 00:15:42,080
buckets.

366
00:15:42,080 --> 00:15:45,460
So if I said, IS 3600
students can access S3

367
00:15:45,460 --> 00:15:48,790
and then I also give you a new
policy that has specific S3

368
00:15:48,790 --> 00:15:53,380
access, this one of an
explicit deny of S3 buckets

369
00:15:53,380 --> 00:15:55,320
will supersede that.

370
00:15:55,320 --> 00:15:59,260
But if I don't explicitly
deny S3 access,

371
00:15:59,260 --> 00:16:02,260
then it's just assumed
that you are denied access.

372
00:16:02,260 --> 00:16:04,140
But if then in another
policy, I grant

373
00:16:04,140 --> 00:16:06,370
you access to a
specific S3 bucket,

374
00:16:06,370 --> 00:16:08,850
you'll get access to that
one but not have access

375
00:16:08,850 --> 00:16:10,920
to any of the other ones.

376
00:16:10,920 --> 00:16:12,220
So that's subtle.

377
00:16:12,220 --> 00:16:16,470
But the idea is, again, I'm
going to explicitly deny what

378
00:16:16,470 --> 00:16:20,370
cannot be superseded at
all, but if it's implicit.

379
00:16:20,370 --> 00:16:23,850
I don't want you to get there,
but if there's a specific use

380
00:16:23,850 --> 00:16:28,210
case, then I can give it to you,
then I don't explicitly deny.

381
00:16:28,210 --> 00:16:30,160
There's also a
resource-based policies

382
00:16:30,160 --> 00:16:32,180
that are attached
obviously to a resource.

383
00:16:32,180 --> 00:16:34,700
So an S3 bucket,
an EC2 instance,

384
00:16:34,700 --> 00:16:37,570
whatever you want to call,
pick your favorite resource,

385
00:16:37,570 --> 00:16:40,270
and that's going to specify
who has access to the resource

386
00:16:40,270 --> 00:16:42,160
and what can be performed on it.

387
00:16:42,160 --> 00:16:44,570
So again, it's applied
to the whole resource.

388
00:16:44,570 --> 00:16:49,030
So you could say, I'm only
going to allow S3 Glacier Deep

389
00:16:49,030 --> 00:16:51,550
Archive to be read
from, because maybe that

390
00:16:51,550 --> 00:16:54,520
is where I'm putting my
company's secure and long term

391
00:16:54,520 --> 00:16:58,270
backup storage or backup
copies, and I don't

392
00:16:58,270 --> 00:17:00,017
need that be deleted ever.

393
00:17:00,017 --> 00:17:01,600
Worst case, we'll
just write new stuff

394
00:17:01,600 --> 00:17:03,392
and we'll just keep
the old stuff in there,

395
00:17:03,392 --> 00:17:07,760
but I never want to let
you delete from that.

396
00:17:07,760 --> 00:17:10,510
And so I can make it a very
explicit blanket resource-based

397
00:17:10,510 --> 00:17:12,440
policy that says, nobody
can delete from this.

398
00:17:12,440 --> 00:17:14,690
The only way you could ever
delete something from that

399
00:17:14,690 --> 00:17:17,440
is for an admin user
that has admin privileges

400
00:17:17,440 --> 00:17:20,680
to go in, remove that
policy, and then go in

401
00:17:20,680 --> 00:17:22,310
and explicitly delete that.

402
00:17:22,310 --> 00:17:24,940
And so the idea here again
being that it's very intentional

403
00:17:24,940 --> 00:17:25,839
steps.

404
00:17:25,839 --> 00:17:28,700
Those very intentional
steps and explicit steps

405
00:17:28,700 --> 00:17:30,835
are what separates
the security here.

406
00:17:34,990 --> 00:17:37,540
So an example of an IAM policy.

407
00:17:37,540 --> 00:17:39,880
So this is what one
would look-- this is what

408
00:17:39,880 --> 00:17:41,410
a JSON document looks like.

409
00:17:41,410 --> 00:17:43,160
So you can read it like this.

410
00:17:43,160 --> 00:17:46,130
So you see these curly
brackets, this one is open,

411
00:17:46,130 --> 00:17:48,050
this one down here is closed.

412
00:17:48,050 --> 00:17:51,370
So that's going to contain
the whole JSON note--

413
00:17:51,370 --> 00:17:53,390
JSON document
information in there.

414
00:17:53,390 --> 00:17:55,660
So it's a dictionary-- very
similar to a dictionary

415
00:17:55,660 --> 00:17:57,910
in Python.

416
00:17:57,910 --> 00:18:00,430
And then you'll see here
that we have-- oops.

417
00:18:00,430 --> 00:18:02,650
We have version,
and so that's going

418
00:18:02,650 --> 00:18:05,360
to specify again the version
that we're working on.

419
00:18:05,360 --> 00:18:08,020
The statement though is
what actually contains

420
00:18:08,020 --> 00:18:11,210
the explicit allow or deny.

421
00:18:11,210 --> 00:18:13,730
So you see in here,
this statement says,

422
00:18:13,730 --> 00:18:20,380
I want to have the effect
of allowing DynamoDB S3

423
00:18:20,380 --> 00:18:23,770
access and these
specific S3 buckets

424
00:18:23,770 --> 00:18:27,590
and this explicit
DynamoDB table name.

425
00:18:27,590 --> 00:18:28,640
It's not blanket.

426
00:18:28,640 --> 00:18:33,390
It's only an allow for these
actions on these resources.

427
00:18:33,390 --> 00:18:38,240
So you see that effect
action resource trio there.

428
00:18:38,240 --> 00:18:42,440
And then within that statement,
that's the square bracket here.

429
00:18:42,440 --> 00:18:44,840
You see that's the
square brackets, a list.

430
00:18:44,840 --> 00:18:46,550
It is a list.

431
00:18:46,550 --> 00:18:49,190
Within that, there's
another statement

432
00:18:49,190 --> 00:18:51,270
or, yeah, another
statement, another effect,

433
00:18:51,270 --> 00:18:53,100
and that's a deny effect.

434
00:18:53,100 --> 00:18:58,430
And that effect denies
access to DynamoDB and S3,

435
00:18:58,430 --> 00:19:04,400
and then it's going to have
but excluding these resources.

436
00:19:04,400 --> 00:19:06,490
So you see there, it's
not resources excluding.

437
00:19:06,490 --> 00:19:08,240
I don't really care
about you guys knowing

438
00:19:08,240 --> 00:19:09,420
exactly the syntax of this.

439
00:19:09,420 --> 00:19:11,690
I just want to show you
roughly how it works.

440
00:19:11,690 --> 00:19:13,790
But see here that
in explicit deny

441
00:19:13,790 --> 00:19:17,100
statement will take precedence
over an allow statement.

442
00:19:17,100 --> 00:19:18,660
So if I deny it--

443
00:19:18,660 --> 00:19:23,220
if I allowed it and then
I explicitly deny it,

444
00:19:23,220 --> 00:19:24,750
that will take precedence.

445
00:19:24,750 --> 00:19:28,040
So like I was saying is if
you're working on the IS 3600

446
00:19:28,040 --> 00:19:32,452
or working under that policy and
it has an explicit deny of S3,

447
00:19:32,452 --> 00:19:34,160
I don't care if I have
anything else that

448
00:19:34,160 --> 00:19:36,600
comes in there that says, you
should be granted S3 access,

449
00:19:36,600 --> 00:19:39,510
even if it's, you should
be granted S3 admin access.

450
00:19:39,510 --> 00:19:41,300
There's still an
explicit deny in there

451
00:19:41,300 --> 00:19:45,270
that will always
take precedence.

452
00:19:45,270 --> 00:19:47,250
So again, just to
show this explicitly

453
00:19:47,250 --> 00:19:51,100
in a flow chart, the way AWS
is reading this on the backend

454
00:19:51,100 --> 00:19:54,010
is it says, if you try to do
something, it's going to say,

455
00:19:54,010 --> 00:19:57,400
first off, is this
permission explicitly denied?

456
00:19:57,400 --> 00:20:00,460
If it's a yes, it doesn't matter
what else happens after that,

457
00:20:00,460 --> 00:20:03,190
you are denied
access to blanket.

458
00:20:03,190 --> 00:20:05,830
If it's not explicitly
denied, it then it

459
00:20:05,830 --> 00:20:08,840
will be asking, OK, well,
is it explicitly allowed?

460
00:20:08,840 --> 00:20:11,510
If it is, then great,
you can access it.

461
00:20:11,510 --> 00:20:14,288
If it's not, you
are still denied.

462
00:20:14,288 --> 00:20:15,830
So you see, it's
more often than not,

463
00:20:15,830 --> 00:20:17,705
you're going to end up
in the deny statement.

464
00:20:17,705 --> 00:20:19,960
It has to be both not
explicitly denied and then

465
00:20:19,960 --> 00:20:22,935
explicitly allowed to allow
you access to the resource.

466
00:20:26,490 --> 00:20:28,570
And so as we talked
about IAM groups,

467
00:20:28,570 --> 00:20:31,240
it's just a nice way
to aggregate people

468
00:20:31,240 --> 00:20:32,120
under one bucket.

469
00:20:32,120 --> 00:20:34,120
And so I can just assign
a policy to the group,

470
00:20:34,120 --> 00:20:36,190
and that policy
trickles down then

471
00:20:36,190 --> 00:20:40,840
to all the users
within that group.

472
00:20:40,840 --> 00:20:43,600
So here's an example of maybe
I have admins, developers,

473
00:20:43,600 --> 00:20:44,470
and testers.

474
00:20:44,470 --> 00:20:46,120
And so these people,
all I have to do

475
00:20:46,120 --> 00:20:50,080
is change the policy
the resource access

476
00:20:50,080 --> 00:20:51,440
from the whole group level.

477
00:20:51,440 --> 00:20:56,390
And each of these individuals
will be given access as well to.

478
00:20:56,390 --> 00:20:58,580
A user can belong to
multiple groups though.

479
00:20:58,580 --> 00:21:00,740
Though remember, that
explicit allow, deny

480
00:21:00,740 --> 00:21:01,920
can come into play here.

481
00:21:01,920 --> 00:21:04,280
So if you ever have somebody
assigned to multiple groups

482
00:21:04,280 --> 00:21:06,330
and something's not
working the way you expect,

483
00:21:06,330 --> 00:21:08,090
look at those explicit
denies and see

484
00:21:08,090 --> 00:21:09,350
if maybe they're
superseding something

485
00:21:09,350 --> 00:21:11,570
that you don't want them
to and then rethink how you

486
00:21:11,570 --> 00:21:14,360
need to structure that policy.

487
00:21:14,360 --> 00:21:15,840
There's no default group though.

488
00:21:15,840 --> 00:21:19,010
So there's not like you can
say, everybody in this--

489
00:21:19,010 --> 00:21:20,660
that's in this
organization can do this

490
00:21:20,660 --> 00:21:23,270
without explicitly adding
everybody to that organization

491
00:21:23,270 --> 00:21:26,580
or adding a policy to a resource
within that whole organization,

492
00:21:26,580 --> 00:21:29,300
there's no default group
that you can assign things to

493
00:21:29,300 --> 00:21:31,020
and you can't nest
the groups either.

494
00:21:31,020 --> 00:21:33,980
So I can't be--

495
00:21:33,980 --> 00:21:36,532
all developers or admins and
all testers or developers

496
00:21:36,532 --> 00:21:37,490
or something like that.

497
00:21:37,490 --> 00:21:39,450
It has to be separate entities.

498
00:21:39,450 --> 00:21:41,333
We really want to avoid
any sort of ambiguity

499
00:21:41,333 --> 00:21:43,250
of what sort of permission
should or shouldn't

500
00:21:43,250 --> 00:21:44,430
be allowed anywhere.

501
00:21:46,970 --> 00:21:49,760
And then the IAM roles,
that's an identity

502
00:21:49,760 --> 00:21:51,660
with specific
permissions added to it.

503
00:21:51,660 --> 00:21:54,110
So again, the way you want
to think about this is,

504
00:21:54,110 --> 00:21:59,750
maybe there are certain
things where I don't--

505
00:21:59,750 --> 00:22:03,000
again, so it's similar to a user
that you attach policies to it.

506
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:06,470
But you don't want to uniquely
associate that policy with just

507
00:22:06,470 --> 00:22:08,420
one user, and you
don't necessarily

508
00:22:08,420 --> 00:22:10,710
want to create a group
for all these users.

509
00:22:10,710 --> 00:22:12,770
You're just saying
that, hey, there's

510
00:22:12,770 --> 00:22:16,730
this task that could
happen, and the access that

511
00:22:16,730 --> 00:22:18,770
would be needed to do
this task, I can just

512
00:22:18,770 --> 00:22:20,130
define it by that role.

513
00:22:20,130 --> 00:22:22,920
And then whether it's a
person, application or service,

514
00:22:22,920 --> 00:22:24,980
I can assign that role
to them and they'll

515
00:22:24,980 --> 00:22:26,370
have that relevant access.

516
00:22:26,370 --> 00:22:27,870
So it allows you
to streamline this.

517
00:22:27,870 --> 00:22:30,270
So if there's common tasks
that need to be done,

518
00:22:30,270 --> 00:22:32,960
maybe it's that
there's a user that

519
00:22:32,960 --> 00:22:36,890
is working through a
automatic setup or some code

520
00:22:36,890 --> 00:22:39,060
on the back end that
needs to be run repeatedly

521
00:22:39,060 --> 00:22:41,030
and they're testing it
out on their platform

522
00:22:41,030 --> 00:22:45,720
or their local environment or
in the cloud on an EC2 instance,

523
00:22:45,720 --> 00:22:48,240
I can assign the role
to that EC2 instance.

524
00:22:48,240 --> 00:22:50,070
And then I can say,
OK, if this role is

525
00:22:50,070 --> 00:22:51,790
all they need to
complete that task,

526
00:22:51,790 --> 00:22:55,570
I can now assign that
IAM role to a service.

527
00:22:55,570 --> 00:22:58,230
I can attach it to
some container service

528
00:22:58,230 --> 00:23:04,290
so that all the containers spun
up have this IAM role attached

529
00:23:04,290 --> 00:23:06,660
and they all have the
same access that developer

530
00:23:06,660 --> 00:23:08,350
had for that task.

531
00:23:08,350 --> 00:23:11,080
So it's just to try to
simplify some of these things.

532
00:23:11,080 --> 00:23:13,170
So I give some examples here.

533
00:23:13,170 --> 00:23:17,100
Granting an IAM user access
to larger EC2 instances

534
00:23:17,100 --> 00:23:18,340
for a specific project.

535
00:23:18,340 --> 00:23:21,090
So again, maybe you're working
on an ASC project for us,

536
00:23:21,090 --> 00:23:24,000
and we all of a sudden
need to use a really

537
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:25,770
beefy computer or a GPU.

538
00:23:25,770 --> 00:23:29,475
Well, rather than
having to go in there

539
00:23:29,475 --> 00:23:31,350
and manually change what
your user can access

540
00:23:31,350 --> 00:23:33,780
and then go back and remove
what you can access and change

541
00:23:33,780 --> 00:23:35,680
some things, I can
just quickly say, well,

542
00:23:35,680 --> 00:23:38,940
here's the IAM
role for GPU access

543
00:23:38,940 --> 00:23:41,470
for data science research.

544
00:23:41,470 --> 00:23:45,090
And once you're done with that
task, I can repeal that role,

545
00:23:45,090 --> 00:23:46,930
and then you don't
have access anymore.

546
00:23:46,930 --> 00:23:48,030
So it simplifies again.

547
00:23:48,030 --> 00:23:50,238
And I can do that for a
bunch of people really quick,

548
00:23:50,238 --> 00:23:52,880
and then remove those
and all that good stuff.

549
00:23:52,880 --> 00:23:54,630
You can use it for
granting an application

550
00:23:54,630 --> 00:23:58,322
access to specific resources,
and this is really useful.

551
00:23:58,322 --> 00:24:00,780
And you'll see this later on
to avoid embedding credentials

552
00:24:00,780 --> 00:24:01,630
in the app.

553
00:24:01,630 --> 00:24:04,320
So let's say that you need to--

554
00:24:04,320 --> 00:24:06,420
in this specific
application, you

555
00:24:06,420 --> 00:24:09,840
need to query some sort of
table, some sort of big database

556
00:24:09,840 --> 00:24:11,010
that you have.

557
00:24:11,010 --> 00:24:13,660
And rather than having
to explicitly put,

558
00:24:13,660 --> 00:24:17,910
well, this is the user
ID and a passkey that

559
00:24:17,910 --> 00:24:21,090
will let you access
that database,

560
00:24:21,090 --> 00:24:22,840
rather than putting
that into the app,

561
00:24:22,840 --> 00:24:24,770
I can just assign
the role or yeah,

562
00:24:24,770 --> 00:24:27,173
the role to that application.

563
00:24:27,173 --> 00:24:28,590
And so then I don't
have this risk

564
00:24:28,590 --> 00:24:30,048
that, well, if
somebody gets access

565
00:24:30,048 --> 00:24:31,830
to the source code
of my app, I don't

566
00:24:31,830 --> 00:24:35,170
have my password and username
embedded in there somewhere.

567
00:24:35,170 --> 00:24:38,910
That's the idea and help
that security out some.

568
00:24:38,910 --> 00:24:41,580
And then yeah, granting access
to resources in your account

569
00:24:41,580 --> 00:24:42,760
or to a user in a
different account.

570
00:24:42,760 --> 00:24:43,950
So it's just that granting.

571
00:24:43,950 --> 00:24:47,600
That's kind of a
blanket statement.

572
00:24:47,600 --> 00:24:49,847
So here's an example
use of an IAM role.

573
00:24:49,847 --> 00:24:51,680
So let's say, again,
you have an application

574
00:24:51,680 --> 00:24:54,620
that runs on an EC2
instance, but needs access

575
00:24:54,620 --> 00:24:56,052
to an S3 bucket.

576
00:24:56,052 --> 00:24:57,510
So the application
is running here.

577
00:24:57,510 --> 00:25:00,800
This rectangle is
representing the EC2 instance.

578
00:25:00,800 --> 00:25:04,310
Well, I can define
an IAM policy that

579
00:25:04,310 --> 00:25:06,860
grants access to a
specific bucket, the photos

580
00:25:06,860 --> 00:25:09,080
bucket within S3.

581
00:25:09,080 --> 00:25:15,170
I can attach that policy to a
role, and I can assume that role

582
00:25:15,170 --> 00:25:17,960
or have that EC2 instance
assume that role such

583
00:25:17,960 --> 00:25:22,070
that it has permission
to access that S3 bucket.

584
00:25:22,070 --> 00:25:23,250
So see, that's the flow.

585
00:25:23,250 --> 00:25:27,990
Attach a policy to a role, have
an instance assume that role,

586
00:25:27,990 --> 00:25:29,543
and then it has that access.

587
00:25:29,543 --> 00:25:30,960
And in the event
that I don't need

588
00:25:30,960 --> 00:25:32,710
it-- don't want it to
have access anymore,

589
00:25:32,710 --> 00:25:34,140
I can repeal that role.

590
00:25:34,140 --> 00:25:35,750
I can pull that role
from them, but I

591
00:25:35,750 --> 00:25:38,332
don't have to necessarily pull
policies and change policies

592
00:25:38,332 --> 00:25:39,540
around or anything like that.

593
00:25:39,540 --> 00:25:41,240
It really simplifies
the amount of coding

594
00:25:41,240 --> 00:25:42,823
I have to do because
then I don't have

595
00:25:42,823 --> 00:25:44,660
to write a bunch of
JSON over and over

596
00:25:44,660 --> 00:25:46,473
that denies and allows
all over the place.

597
00:25:46,473 --> 00:25:48,390
And that's going to get
messy and you're going

598
00:25:48,390 --> 00:25:49,685
to probably mess something up.

599
00:25:52,380 --> 00:25:55,470
And then there's also
the account root user.

600
00:25:55,470 --> 00:25:58,890
You won't see in this course
unless you create your own AWS

601
00:25:58,890 --> 00:26:00,210
account entirely.

602
00:26:00,210 --> 00:26:02,230
None of you will have
root user access.

603
00:26:02,230 --> 00:26:07,200
There's only going to be one
root user that exists usually,

604
00:26:07,200 --> 00:26:10,290
and it's also not
recommended to use that.

605
00:26:10,290 --> 00:26:12,990
The root user has
access to everything.

606
00:26:12,990 --> 00:26:15,790
That user can do anything they
want to do on the account.

607
00:26:15,790 --> 00:26:17,370
They can set up any resources.

608
00:26:17,370 --> 00:26:20,140
The thing is, they can also
assign any policies, roles,

609
00:26:20,140 --> 00:26:21,100
repeal anything.

610
00:26:21,100 --> 00:26:22,890
So access to that
root user account

611
00:26:22,890 --> 00:26:26,440
is absolutely critical
to keep secure.

612
00:26:26,440 --> 00:26:29,550
And so the real
way you do this is

613
00:26:29,550 --> 00:26:32,010
even if you are the main
admin at your company,

614
00:26:32,010 --> 00:26:34,420
you're the only person who
knows anything about AWS,

615
00:26:34,420 --> 00:26:37,120
you'll set up the user--
you'll set up the AWS account,

616
00:26:37,120 --> 00:26:39,160
you'll be granted root access.

617
00:26:39,160 --> 00:26:40,702
But then the second
you get in there,

618
00:26:40,702 --> 00:26:42,243
the first thing you
should do is just

619
00:26:42,243 --> 00:26:43,770
go create an IAM
role for yourself

620
00:26:43,770 --> 00:26:47,070
or an IAM user for yourself,
and you can grant them

621
00:26:47,070 --> 00:26:48,217
a lot of permissions.

622
00:26:48,217 --> 00:26:49,800
You could grant them
admin permissions

623
00:26:49,800 --> 00:26:52,600
to mostly everything,
but it's still

624
00:26:52,600 --> 00:26:54,910
going to be all controlled
through that user account

625
00:26:54,910 --> 00:26:58,820
and only that user account
will be the one you use.

626
00:26:58,820 --> 00:27:01,960
Keep that root
account to the side.

627
00:27:01,960 --> 00:27:03,940
You really want to--

628
00:27:03,940 --> 00:27:06,610
like I suggested here, disable
remove your account root user

629
00:27:06,610 --> 00:27:07,360
access keys.

630
00:27:07,360 --> 00:27:09,970
You really don't want to
be accessing from that

631
00:27:09,970 --> 00:27:13,570
unless absolutely necessary.

632
00:27:13,570 --> 00:27:15,830
It is the biggest
security hole in this.

633
00:27:15,830 --> 00:27:18,130
And that's the
nature of security.

634
00:27:18,130 --> 00:27:20,860
Is, it's hard to have--

635
00:27:20,860 --> 00:27:24,670
actually, it's impossible to
have a perfect security system.

636
00:27:24,670 --> 00:27:27,260
What we try to do
is mitigate risks.

637
00:27:27,260 --> 00:27:29,710
And the root user is
the way we do this.

638
00:27:29,710 --> 00:27:33,160
Is, we put everything into IAM
users and roles and policies

639
00:27:33,160 --> 00:27:35,860
and groups, and
know that there is

640
00:27:35,860 --> 00:27:40,420
one super user above all that
can technically allow access

641
00:27:40,420 --> 00:27:41,117
to everything.

642
00:27:41,117 --> 00:27:42,700
But that means we
just need to protect

643
00:27:42,700 --> 00:27:44,800
that one user account
and everything else

644
00:27:44,800 --> 00:27:46,150
is controlled separately.

645
00:27:46,150 --> 00:27:47,330
That's the hope with this.

646
00:27:47,330 --> 00:27:48,812
So keep that in mind.

647
00:27:48,812 --> 00:27:50,770
Again, we won't do it
explicitly in this course

648
00:27:50,770 --> 00:27:56,550
because you won't be asked to
do that, but that is the risk.

649
00:27:56,550 --> 00:27:57,180
And so great.

